comments:
Sociology provides a unique way to look at human behavior and the world. Sociology is the systematic study of the groups and societies in which people live. In this introductory course, we examine and analyze how social structures and cultures are created, maintained, and most importantly, how they affect behavior. The course deconstructs our taken for granted world of social interactions and behaviors and examines what theory and research can tell about human social behavior. &#8232;&#8232;

Students raved about Professor Nopper\'s Intro to Sociology course, calling it \"absolutely fabulous\" Students stated that the selected readings were \"GREAT,\" \"interesting,\" and contributed to the overall flow of the class. A majority of students lauded the dynamic use of both lecture and PowerPoint slides, which provided a more lively atmosphere. &#8232;

&#8232;Students heaped praise upon Professor Nopper. One student declared that she \"clearly conveys all information, provokes stimulating and valuable debates, and at the same time creates a pleasant atmosphere in the classroom\". Another student stated that although the course was not taken \"only to fulfill a requirement\", as the student was not a sociology major, the course still was \"was one of the most rewarding courses I have taken at Penn\" due to Professor Nopper\'s extensive \"planning and prep\". Students praised Professor Nopper for the structure of the course and her receptiveness and accessibility. One student went as far as to say that \"her lectures inspired me throughout the semester and motivated me to do better inside and outside of the classroom\".

Students stated that they would recommend this course to all students, both Sociology majors and non-majors.
